text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Canadian eh%0a:Author: sathyas%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 04.04.2021 - 10:56%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210418-225106-498920#%0a* [-18.04.2021 - 15:51-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210418-225106-498920#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aShort Article detailing the use of 'eh' in Canadian English%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aOne of the common stereotypes about Canadians and their speaking is that their speech is littered with eh's. The Canadian eh is a word added at the end of declarative sentences, and it is similar to saying 'right' or 'don't you' at the end of a sentence. It turns the sentence from a declarative to a conformational often. Here are some examples:%0a%0aYou have a new cat.%0aYou have a new cat, eh?%0aYou have a new cat, right?%0a%0aThis speech phenomena is most commonly found in speakers of central Canada (Toronto). A few studies agree that the use of 'eh' is more prevalent amongst lower class, uneducated, and rural men. It is used in two different positions of a sentence.%0a%0aThe first is at the end of a clause (usually a sentence):%0aYou have a new cat, eh?%0aYou have a new cat eh so make sure you get some catnip.%0a%0aThe second is as a standalone utterance.%0aEh? Can you repeat your cat's name?%0a%0aIt cannot be used within a sentence or clause:%0aYou eh have a new cat?%0a%0aAs stated earlier, the use of eh is often a "conformational" to transform a declarative statement to a "request for confirmation." Hence, phrases like 'don't you' or 'right' in standard English perform the same purpose. Besides the use in questions, 'eh' is also commonly used with imperatives and narratives. The imperative eh replaces phrases such as 'will', 'won't', 'would'. The narrative, or anecdotal, eh is used at the end of a clause within a setence.%0a%0aImperative example:%0aThink about it, won't you?%0aThink about it eh?%0a%0aNarrative example:%0aSo I find this cat, eh, and he tries to bite me, eh.%0a%0a'Eh' is so prevalent within Canadian speech due to the vast amount of use cases. It is used to confirm that the speaker is understanding the narrative. There are a few semantic differences with English translations which allow 'eh' to be used even more often.%0aFor example:%0a%0aI have a new cat, eh?%0aI have a new cat, don't I?%0aI have a new cat, right?%0a%0aBoth sentences are grammatically correct, however the standard English dialect does not make semantic sense. The Canadian 'eh' is used solely as confirm the listener's understanding and does not suggest the speaker does not know they have a cat.%0a%0aThe only restriction for using 'eh' is that the assumptions made are generally weak. It cannot be used for imperatives. For example, a army general cannot say:%0a%0a"Forward march, eh!"%0a%0aThere is a strong implied assumption that the general's troops will follow their command, so it does not make semantic sense to add 'eh'.%0a%0a%0aHopefully this can act as a blueprint to help you all speak slightly more Canadian.%0a%0a%0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0aFamily Guy clip of stereotypical eh usage: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-5VTYDOSFIk%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
